    "symbol": "IPNFT",
    "name": "Autophagy Activator Drug Discovery Platform",
    "description": "Ageing is associated with the decline in the capacity of the autophagy pathway to degrade dysfunctional and damaging cellular components, such as protein aggregates and mitochondria. Dysfunctional autophagy, in turn, undermines other cellular functions including DNA repair, metabolism and survival. Therefore, activation of autophagy is considered a promising therapeutic approach to combat ageing and age-related diseases. A large number of screens has been performed and published to date, these have identified a wide range of small molecules that stimulate initiation of autophagy. Prof. Korolchuck lab proposes to initiate a drug discovery program with the aim of identifying novel bioactive autophagy inducers.",
    "image": "ipfs://bafybeibya66qtgrwdgzhbs4r6ken2l4jn6l3jtboo75wcmx2ctibqstl2y",
    "externalUrl": "https://mint.molecule.to/ipnft/2",
    "initialSymbol": "VITA-FAST",
    "organization": "Newcastle University",
    "topic": "Aging ",
    "trlValue": "trl-2",
    "trlRationale": "The project has conducted extensive experimental work including high-throughput phenotypic screening across thousands of compounds, validation of screening platforms with FDA-approved drugs identifying 12 novel autophagy inducers, three rounds of NCE synthesis, and in vitro testing demonstrating 10-100x potency improvements. However, the work remains primarily in simplified in vitro cell models (Npc1-/- and Atg5-/- knockout cells). While worm healthspan studies are mentioned as 'ongoing,' no completed disease-relevant in vivo efficacy data in mammalian disease models is presented.",
